3:["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["How Funding Works on ","Orderly Network"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates SEI/USDT funding rates hourly using a time-weighted average price mechanism across its shared order book. The protocol aggregates funding payments from multiple frontend partners, creating a unified rate that reflects cross-chain sentiment. Funding rates are determined by the premium/discount between the perpetual price and the underlying SEI spot index, with payments exchanged directly between long and short position holders. The shared liquidity model means funding rates can deviate significantly from centralized exchanges during periods of frontend-specific demand imbalances."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SEI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI/USDT presents compelling arbitrage opportunities due to SEI's role as a sector-specific Layer 1 focused on trading infrastructure. The token's correlation with broader DeFi trends creates predictable funding rate cycles, particularly during network upgrade announcements or ecosystem expansions. Orderly Network's position as infrastructure for multiple DEX frontends means SEI funding rates often lag behind centralized exchange movements, creating profitable arbitrage windows."}]]}],[["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SEI/USDT funding rates on Orderly Network have shown distinct patterns tied to the SEI ecosystem's development cycles. During major network upgrades or partnership announcements, rates typically turn strongly positive as retail traders accumulate long positions. The shared order book structure means rates often remain elevated for 3-6 hours longer than on centralized exchanges. Weekend periods frequently see negative funding rates as institutional activity decreases across Orderly's frontend partners. Monthly expiration cycles create predictable rate compression patterns, with funding typically normalizing 24-48 hours before major DeFi protocol updates."}]]}],["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-DEX Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network's unique architecture creates arbitrage opportunities between its various frontend partners and external DEXs. SEI funding rates often diverge by 0.01-0.03% from rates on traditional perpetual platforms during high volatility periods. The protocol's NEAR and EVM compatibility allows for sophisticated cross-chain arbitrage strategies using native SEI bridges. Traders can exploit rate differentials by maintaining positions across multiple Orderly frontends, though this requires careful management of gas costs and bridge delays. The shared liquidity model means large positions can influence rates across the entire network, creating opportunities for informed traders to front-run rate adjustments."}]]}],"$L8"],"$L9"]}]
