8:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Trading SEI perpetuals on Orderly Network requires understanding the platform's multi-layered risk structure. Frontend partner reliability becomes crucial as technical issues with individual interfaces can prevent timely position management. The shared order book model means liquidation cascades can propagate rapidly across all connected platforms, potentially amplifying SEI's natural volatility. Bridge risks are significant for cross-chain strategies, as SEI deposits may be delayed during network congestion. Funding rate calculations can become unpredictable during extreme market stress when multiple frontends experience different liquidity conditions, requiring constant monitoring of the underlying rate methodology."}]]}]
9:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often are SEI/USDT funding rates updated on Orderly Network?","answer":"Orderly Network updates SEI/USDT funding rates every hour using a time-weighted average of the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The shared order book aggregates data from all connected frontends to calculate a unified rate that applies across the entire ecosystem."},{"question":"What makes SEI funding rate arbitrage unique on Orderly's shared infrastructure?","answer":"Orderly's shared order book means SEI funding rates reflect sentiment across multiple DEX frontends simultaneously, often creating lag compared to centralized exchanges. This infrastructure allows for arbitrage between different frontend partners and provides opportunities when cross-chain SEI sentiment diverges from the aggregated rate."},{"question":"How do Orderly Network's fees impact SEI/USDT funding rate strategies?","answer":"Orderly charges 0.02% maker and 0.05% taker fees on SEI/USDT trades, which must be factored into funding rate arbitrage calculations. The shared liquidity model means effective fees can vary based on which frontend you use, as some partners offer fee rebates or additional incentives."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage SEI funding rates between Orderly frontends?","answer":"While all Orderly frontends share the same order book and funding rates, different interfaces may offer varying fee structures or additional rewards. Cross-frontend arbitrage focuses more on user experience optimization and potential frontend-specific incentives rather than rate differentials."}]}]
